self.lscp_obj_value = lscp.problem.objective.value()
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 6, 29, 0, 43, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 910112385, 'comment_body': 'Look into this later.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 6, 29, 15, 28, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 910113514, 'comment_body': 'Look into this later.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 6, 29, 15, 29, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 910389589, 'comment_body': "@jGaboardi I updated the LSCPB class to include this attribute. I also updated the from_cost_matrix class method to set this attribute. However, it seems my implementation isn't quite in line with the package style and I'd like some feedback. Thanks!", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 6, 29, 20, 34, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'erinrolson', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 910462797, 'comment_body': 'hmmm. I see what you mean. I think `lscp_obj_value` does not need to be set within `LSCPB`, but can be set directly after instantiation. This is because it is not used until we are adding the facility constraint. For example:

```python
lscpb = LSCPB(name, model)
lscpb.lscp_obj_value = lscp.problem.objective.value()

...

FacilityModelBuilder.add_facility_constraint(
    lscpb, lscpb.problem, lscpb.lscp_obj_value
)
```
